{
  "texts": [
    "9 use a survey, asking authors why they cited a specific paper.",
    "However, surveys may have response biases and are difficult to scale.",
    "Hoppe et al.",
    "use the timing of when references were added-before or after peer review-as a signal of their substantive or rhetorical nature, which is more scalable but relies on the existence of multiple versions of a paper.",
    "Lastly, even if the classification challenge was resolved, causality would be difficult to establish, as it is very unlikely that any two communities that differ in their citing practices do not differ in any other consequential ways."
  ]
}